<ul>
<li><strong>Username:</strong> <span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/proteus-steinmetz" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(1804992); return false;"><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=1804992&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1582964913" alt="Proteus Steinmetz" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=1804992)" /></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/proteus-steinmetz" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(1804992); return false;">Proteus Steinmetz</a></span></li>
</ul>
<ul>
<li><strong>Applying For:</strong> System Administration</li>
</ul>
<ul>
<li><strong>Experience:</strong> If this site truly requires a proper system administrator, then I can assist the SCP Wiki team in this field. I have about 8 years of experience in system administration, and I am currently a full-time penetration tester and cybersecurity researcher. As a system administrator, I have experience across various operating systems (Solaris, Red Hat Linux, Windows Server, MacOS, etc.) and software management suites. I also have experience with servers, IT security systems, and other critical components of an organization's IT infrastructure. I also have a strong background in system automation and virtualization.</li>
</ul>
<ul>
<li><strong>Professional Experience:</strong> I have experience managing critical infrastructure for the Department of Defense, the Federal Aviation Administration, and the United States Air Force. I was in charge of the primary and secondary networks that handled real-time air traffic control operations for the FAA at multiple sites. In the Air Force, I was the lead member of the radar network responsible for providing weather and air traffic data to both military and civilian satellite sites. For the Department of Defense, I managed thousands of classified machines, intrusion detection systems, and user accounts as well as sensitive proprietary applications.</li>
</ul>
<ul>
<li><strong>Any professional accolades, certifications, or qualifications for this skillset:</strong> Bachelor's in Information Technology with a security focus, CompTIA Linux+, CompTIA Network+, CompTIA Security+, OSCP, OSCE, Certified Ethical Hacker v10, Penetration Testing Professional v5, Certified Information Systems Security Professional, Certified Information Systems Auditor, Coined and awarded an Air Force achievement medal by Chief of Staff General Mark A. Welsh III of the United States Air Force for identifying and designing a fix action for a significant network design flaw, AFSC Oustanding Airman of the Year across the global Air Force talent pool, Awarded SrA Below-The-Zone, Diamond Sharp Award, Air Force Air Mobility Command Inspector General's Outstanding Performer Award</li>
</ul>
<ul>
<li><strong>What technologies are you familiar with within your area of expertise? For instance, do you use Jira to track QA issues? Do you work with JUnit for Unit tests? Ever used Docker? Tell me about your abilities here:</strong> JIRA is fine enough, the government uses its own proprietary system, but the only issue with JIRA is if you have someone set it up poorly. The program also handles emails pretty wonky. My last thing to note about it is that it gets expensive quickly as the user pool increases for licenses. For unit testing, I enjoy TestNG over JUnit since it has a bit more functions available but JUnit is fine too. I prefer to use Kubernetes in general, but it also works well alongside Docker. I have a lot of automation experience since in sysadmin that's the name of the game. I love bash and batch scripting but a few languages I have direct experience with are SQL, C, C++, Perl, Python, C#, Java, Powershell, and .NET as a technology in general. On the cybersecurity side of the house, I employ Kali Linux as most do, with BurpSuite and Metasploit.</li>
</ul>
<p>Overall, I've pretty much used most of the standard sysadmin tools over the years and can learn anything new quickly based on prior experience.</p>

