<p><strong>Username:</strong> ManyMeats</p>
<p><strong>Experience:</strong> I am an IT professional with 12 years of experience in systems administration and technical support. Previous jobs include 'Solutions Engineer' for a managed services firm, 'Network Engineer' for a Fortune 500 company in their network operations center, a 'Storage and Backup Engineer' for a US leader in insurance, and most recently full system support for a State agency in Wisconsin. During this time, I have accumulated a tremendous level of exposure to different technologies including more than half of my professional career building, supporting, and maintaining 24/7/365 systems in a data center or hosted environment.</p>
<p><strong>Professional Experience:</strong> I would list myself as &quot;advanced&quot; in the following items: Windows Server 2008-2016, Office 365, Citrix VDI-in-a-box, VMWare (especially NTX and Horizons), Commvault backup and recovery, Hitachi and NetApp SANS, SQL Server, Powershell, and Cisco switches.</p>
<p>I would consider myself &quot;intermediate&quot; or to have tertiary experience with the following items: RedHat (5, 6, 7), Oracle (11, 12), Veeam, Adaptive firewall appliances such as Cisco ASAs Palo Alto devices, racking and cabling, cable termination, and other general data center tasks. I'm sure there are other miscellaneous things I could probably list.</p>
<p><strong>Any professional accolades, certifications, or qualifications for this skill set:</strong> I have a Bachelors in Management Information Systems and a Bachelors in Business Administration (w/ minor in CompSci). I have the following vendor-specific accreditations: Commvault Certified Engineer, VMware Certified Professional, CCNA-Routing&amp;Switching, A+ Certification.</p>
<p><strong>What technologies are you familiar with in your area?</strong>: I am familiar with a number of issue and ticket tracking items such as Spiceworks, ServiceNow, and Numera Footprints. In the IT world, fast adaptation to things like this is necessary for survival. Additionally, I do a lot of cross-work with application developers, so I am familiar with github and Jira for iteration and issue tracking, however I am not a frequent end-user for these softwares myself.</p>

